From: jaewun <jaewun@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] scsi: ufs: don't synchronize_irq in ufshcd_suspend (host PM)

A prior fix ("scsi: ufs: don't synchronize_irq in ufshcd_disable_irq during
PM") made ufshcd_disable_irq() mask with disable_irq_nosync() while
ufshcd_relinking() (pm_op_in_progress || relink_poll_active). That covered the
WLUN suspend/resume relink path, where pm_op_in_progress is set by
__ufshcd_wl_suspend()/__ufshcd_wl_resume().

The host-controller suspend helper ufshcd_suspend() runs from
ufshcd_system_suspend()/ufshcd_runtime_suspend(), OUTSIDE that window:
pm_op_in_progress has already been cleared by the time the host .suspend
callback runs, so ufshcd_relinking() is false and ufshcd_disable_irq() takes
the SYNCHRONOUS disable_irq() -> synchronize_irq() path here. hba->irq is a
threaded, IRQF_ONESHOT line; under load its threaded handler
(ufshcd_threaded_intr) is in-flight on the quiescing controller and
synchronize_irq() then blocks forever -> the suspend HARD-WEDGES (the host
stalls in dpm_suspend with no watchdog, requiring a power cycle). On a non-MCQ
controller this is reachable on essentially every loaded system suspend.

Restoring synchronize_irq() is not an option (it IS the wedge). But simply
dropping to disable_irq_nosync() would also drop the ordering that drained an
in-flight threaded handler before ufshcd_setup_clocks(hba, false) gates the
register clocks a few instructions later -- an in-flight ufshcd_threaded_intr
reading REG_INTERRUPT_STATUS on a gated block can raise an unclocked-access
fault.

Use disable_hardirq() instead: it masks the line and waits only for the
*hardirq* (bounded -- never the stuck threaded handler), and reports whether a
threaded handler is still in-flight. If one is, undo the mask and abort the
suspend with -EBUSY (recoverable: the PM core retries / the system suspend is
cleanly failed) rather than wedging or racing the clock gate. The common idle
suspend has no in-flight handler, so disable_hardirq() returns true and the
path proceeds normally. enable_irq() (not ufshcd_enable_irq()) is used on the
abort path because hba->is_irq_enabled is still true there, so the wrapper
would no-op and leak the disable depth.

This extends the nosync tradeoff already accepted by the relinking path in
ufshcd_disable_irq() to the host-suspend descent that sits outside it.

Signed-off-by: jaewun <jaewun@users.noreply.github.com>
---
diff --git a/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c b/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
index 9ceb6d6..6d30ce8 100644
--- a/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
+++ b/drivers/ufs/core/ufshcd.c
@@ -10380,10 +10380,32 @@ static int ufshcd_suspend(struct ufs_hba *hba)
 	if (!hba->is_powered)
 		return 0;
 	/*
-	 * Disable the host irq as host controller as there won't be any
-	 * host controller transaction expected till resume.
+	 * Disable the host irq. hba->irq is a threaded, IRQF_ONESHOT line whose
+	 * synchronous disable_irq() runs synchronize_irq(). This host .suspend
+	 * helper runs OUTSIDE the WLUN suspend's pm_op_in_progress window, so
+	 * ufshcd_disable_irq() would take the synchronizing path here; under load
+	 * the threaded handler (ufshcd_threaded_intr) is in-flight on the
+	 * quiescing controller and synchronize_irq() then blocks forever -- the
+	 * suspend HARD-WEDGES (dpm_suspend stalls, no watchdog -> power cycle).
+	 *
+	 * We must not synchronize_irq() (the wedge), but must also not gate the
+	 * controller register clocks below (ufshcd_setup_clocks(hba, false)) while
+	 * the threaded handler is still doing register MMIO -- an unclocked access
+	 * can fault. disable_hardirq() masks the line and waits only for the
+	 * hardirq (bounded), returning false if a threaded handler is still
+	 * in-flight; in that case undo the mask and abort the suspend (-EBUSY,
+	 * recoverable/retried) rather than wedge or race the clock gate. The
+	 * common idle suspend has no in-flight handler, so this returns true and
+	 * proceeds normally. enable_irq() (not ufshcd_enable_irq()) balances the
+	 * mask because hba->is_irq_enabled is still true on this path.
 	 */
-	ufshcd_disable_irq(hba);
+	if (hba->is_irq_enabled) {
+		if (!disable_hardirq(hba->irq)) {
+			enable_irq(hba->irq);
+			return -EBUSY;
+		}
+		hba->is_irq_enabled = false;
+	}
 	ret = ufshcd_setup_clocks(hba, false);
 	if (ret) {
 		ufshcd_enable_irq(hba);
